#OnTheGo

CRCESI conducts handwashing, deworming initiative

The Center for Recollect Community Engagement and Social Involvement (CRCESI) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) held a ’Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon’ program focusing on handwashing and deworming at the Main Lobby on November 11.

This outreach program was in collaboration with the University’s Biology Students’ Association (BioSA) and the University Health and Services Department.

CRCESI Director, Rev. Fr. Rouel Sia, OAR, reminded the children of the purpose and goal of the ’Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon’ in his opening speech.

“Dumdomi nga [atong] aim diri, ang atong katuyuan [karon] kay para makatabang kami kaninyo, unta magmalumbuon ug magpadayon kini, welcome sa USJ-R og enjoy,” he said.

Moreover, the program proceeded with the Department of Mathematics and Sciences Professor, Dr. Julios Dequillo, in discussing the importance, effects, and essentiality of handwashing in children’s development and hygiene.

“In their age, if they have this practice already, mostly they will be able to train themselves and input this [knowledge] into their system as normal and will be practiced all throughout their lives [contributing] to the development of their personal hygiene,” he said.

A demonstration of the techniques on how to properly wash their hands was conducted by Dequillo and the USJ-R BioSA student officers with the selected children.

In an interview, USJ-R BioSA President Kyle Jero Dico acknowledged the presence of the faculty, officers, and student volunteers who attended the program, together with 55 out of 68 children in Carbon.

“I encourage every Josenian to participate in these outreach activities because it allows us to ground ourselves in the experiences of the people by interacting with them, enhancing our leadership skills and empathy [towards] others,” he added.

Furthermore, the children lined up for the deworming session with the Health and Services Department, followed by the distribution of handwashing kits.

DOT Region 7, THMD conduct FBSE seminar

The Department of Tourism (DOT) Regional Office 7 held a Filipino Brand of Service Excellence (FBSE) workshop in partnership with the University of San Jose-Recoletos Tourism and Hospitality Management Department (USJ-R THMD) at USJ-R Basak Campus Audio-Visual Room (AVR) on Saturday, November 11.

The program tackled the Filipinos’ hospitality through FBSE which is believed to be essential in making every aspect of tourism in carrying Filipino values.

FBSE envisioned its goals to standardize the positive traits of hospitality and service that can be portrayed by all domestic and international stakeholders to make the “Filipino tourism workforce ready for a changed world.”

Moreover, Environmental Planner Ruel Rigor Javier of DOT-Region 7 highlighted the importance of having the Filipino brand warmth from arrival to departure and “its pursuit to consistently meet and surpass the guests’ needs and provide them with a memorable and fun experience.”

Assistant Project Officer Riane Vicariel Sinadjan firmly believed that the students who attended the seminar are the “ambassadors of Filipino core values,” and the lessons they will learn will be carried out in their future endeavors.

“I believe madala ra jod ni nila anywhere they go. They are the representation of [hospitable] people and the future workforce of the [hospitable] industry,” she expressed.

Meanwhile, the Chairperson of the seminar, Diana Marie Lapas, shared her gratitude for the opportunity given as they were the first batch to experience the FBSE seminar and for the wisdom the event had instilled in them.

“We have the foundation na to be used sa among workforce and with that, we really do have the advantage nga we have the training in the field,” Lapas stated.

The second batch of the FBSE seminar-workshop will be held next Saturday, November 18.

[ERRATA: The previous version of this article published on November 12, 2023 at 11:31 a.m., contained errors. The article has been updated at 3:30 p.m. to rectify the following mistakes: Sinadjan was referred to as the ”Assistant Project Officer” but now corrected to ”Tourism instructor.” It was also clarified that Javier is not associated with DOT-Region 7. The editors would like to apologize for the errors.]

USJ-R JPSS opens Polsci Days '23

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Josenian Political Science Society (USJ-R JPSS) kickstarted their Polsci Days 2023 at the USJ-R Main Lobby on Friday afternoon November 10.

With the theme, ”TINUGYANAY: ANG PAG PADAYON SA PAGLAMBO SA ATONG PANAGHIUSA” the event fosters student connections to enhance their academic journey.

Crisjer Cadampog, a Political Science professor, expressed his gratitude to the success of the program and intensified how the event is geared towards ”not merely an academic endeavor, but as a holistic experience that encompasses both academic and non-academic activities.”

”Political Science Days provide an opportunity for students to test their knowledge and engage in scholarly discourse and exchange ideas to deepen their understanding of Political Science,” Cadampog added.

Meanwhile, the President of JPSS, Trisha Acasio, shared how happy she is for the success of the opening program with Josenian alumni returning to witness this year's Polsci Days.

"Everything is put together even though daghan mi’g problems na face but at the same time we still managed to keep everyone present and to participate with the activities," she stated.

The two-day program will culminate with Mr. and Ms. Polsci at the USJ-R Basak Campus on Saturday afternoon, November 11.

#OnTheGo

VP-Acad mandates Josenians to complete online evaluations for educators

The Office of the Vice-President for Academics and Research issued a memorandum on November 9, 2023 that requires all students to comply with the educators' online evaluations as a crucial component of their final examination in an effort to assess teachers' performance during the first semester of the Academic Year 2023-2024.

According to the memo, the Student Evaluation of Teacher Effectiveness (SETE) will be administered online from November 13 to December 8, 2023.

Students will answer the assessment through their Student Information System (SIS) account under the ”Performance Evaluation” tab in the dashboard.

Additionally, the faculty members are encouraged to stress the importance of evaluating their teachers' instructional performance to their students.

This initiative aims to enhance class management and lesson delivery, contributing to continuous quality improvement mechanisms.

[LITERARY]

From Zamboanga, with Love
by Louella Grace Eroma | Josenian Contributor

“Angel Grace, what do you want to be when you grow up?” I asked my sister while sitting in the chair in our garden.

“I want to be an architect one day, Kuya Aldee, and build a house for our parents,” she replied with a huge smile on her face.

My sister loves to draw buildings and houses, and she loves math too.

“What about you, Kuya Aldee, what is your dream?” she asked me.

“I want to become a lawyer one day and help the people who need legal advice and other legal assistance. And aside from that, I want to be the mayor of Zamboanga City,” I replied, smiling back at her.

“Wow, that‘s great, Kuya. It’s a long way to becoming the mayor of our city, especially since there are a lot of people fighting for that position. I hope and pray to God and Our Lady of the Pillar for you,” she said.

Yes, we are devotees of Our Lady of the Pillar, our patroness here in Zamboanga City.

Our mother called us for dinner and her voice could be heard outside.

“You go ahead, Angel Grace. I need to clean up the mess first,” I said to her before leaving.

Sometimes, being the eldest in the family is not easy. There are many responsibilities that you need to take care of, which can be tiring at times.

I went inside our house after cleaning and they were still eating. I sat down in a chair and got my food.

lAldee, Angel told me that you want to be mayor of Zamboanga City soon,” my mother said.

“Yes, Mama, I want to follow in my father’s footsteps,” I replied.

“Are you sure, Aldee? Being the mayor of Zamboanga City is not easy. You will deal with lots of paperwork, sign documents, and face the crowd,” my father said.

“But if that’s what you want, then I will support you,” Papa added.

“Muchísimas gracias (thank you), Papa,” I said and hugged him.

“Study well, Aldee,” he replied.

I have chosen to pursue a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science in college. This is the best degree program for me because I want to become a lawyer and study in Cebu City.

I decided to keep my decision to study in Cebu City a secret from my parents until after my graduation.

I know that it will be difficult to study in a city where I don’t speak its language, Cebuano. Our mother tongue here in Zamboanga City is Chavacano, a Spanish-based creole. This is why our city is also known as “Asia's Latin City.”

Dinner was over, and it was Angel Grace’s turn to wash the dishes while I prepared my things for school the next day to attend our graduation orientation.

While scrolling through my mother’s phone, I saw some announcements from our school and found out that I was the class valedictorian! I was surprised and delighted.

”Mom, Dad, look!” I exclaimed.

“Wow, Aldee, congratulations! You made it. We’re so proud of you,” my mother said. They were very happy with the news.

The next day, my mother woke me up and reminded me about the orientation.

I went straight to the bathroom while my mother cooked breakfast for me.

After taking a shower, I went to my bedroom to put on my uniform and eat my breakfast.

“Hurry up, Aldee! Your dad is waiting for you in the car!” my mom shouted from downstairs.

I was brushing my teeth at the time and in a hurry as well. I grabbed some of my things and went to the car.

As I made my way to school, I was met with a sea of students, all rushing to get to class. The crowd was so thick that I was nearly late. Luckily, I arrived safely after five minutes.

While walking to my classroom, I almost fell down the stairs.

Fortunately, Jahida, a Tausug girl who has been my confidante and best friend since grade school, saw me.

Jahida asked if I was alright, and I smiled in reply.

“Alhamdulillah, Aldee. I’m glad nothing bad happened to you,” she said.

I continued on my way to class.

Our class adviser was observing us and waiting for our principal.

“Class, please minimize your noise,” our adviser said. But no one was listening to her.

Our class adviser was furious, having repeatedly told us to quiet down.

“Please have discipline. You are now about to enter college life, but your behavior still looks like that of high school students. Please,” she said to us.

Then the principal came to our classroom and said, “What's all the commotion about here?” Everyone was silent.

The graduation orientation has begun, and the speakers are presenting their agenda and the details of our graduation ceremony.

“For the practice, we will start on Monday at one in the afternoon. Everyone must join the graduation practice, otherwise, you cannot attend the graduation ceremony. This is only one round of practice,” the principal said.

“And everyone must attend the baccalaureate mass, too. Attendance will be checked in there, as well as the distribution of the garlands,” she added.

Since we were already informed of what to do, we were dismissed early by the principal.

My mom decided to pick me up at our school since my dad couldn’t due to his heavy workload at the city hall.

We were going to the pueblo (town) to wait for my dad, since his work ends at 5 p.m.

“Mang kunambre io (Mom, I’m hungry),” I said.

“Io tamen kunambre ya noy (I’m hungry too, son),” she replied.

Our stomachs were growling, and we were hungry. So we headed to the mall in search of food, but the restaurants were packed and the prices were high. My mom suggested we go to Paseo del Mar instead.

My dad texted me that he was about to leave his office.

Sender: Dad

Aldee, please tell your mom that I’m almost done with my work here. I’ll go out at 5 p.m. and also please tell your mom that we’ll go to Pasonanca later on. Meet me at the entrance of the city hall. I love you.

Sent to: Aldee

“Mom, Dad texted me and said he’s almost out. We'll meet him at the city hall entrance,” I informed my mother.

“Okay, let him know we're on our way,” she replied.

Sender: Aldee

Dad, I just told Mom about this and she said we'll go there. We're now at Paseo del Mar eating. See you later, Dad.

Sent to: Dad

As I looked around the town, I smiled.

I really love my city, and I'm proud to be a Zamboangueño.

At five o’clock in the afternoon, we met up with my dad.

“Hello, Dad. How’s work?" I asked him.

“Very tiring, Aldee,” he replied.

“How's your orientation? Anyway, congratulations in advance for making it, and for moving on to your next journey.” He said and hugged me.

My dad seemed to be struggling to say something to me.

“What is it, Dad?” I asked.

He couldn't hide it anymore.

“What about you, Kuya Aldee, what is your dream?” she asked me.

“I want to become a lawyer one day and help the people who need legal advice and other legal assistance. And aside from that, I want to be the mayor of Zamboanga City,” I replied, smiling back at her.

“Wow, that‘s great, Kuya. It’s a long way to becoming the mayor of our city, especially since there are a lot of people fighting for that position. I hope and pray to God and Our Lady of the Pillar for you,” she said.

Yes, we are devotees of Our Lady of the Pillar, our patroness here in Zamboanga City.

Our mother called us for dinner and her voice could be heard outside.

“You go ahead, Angel Grace. I need to clean up the mess first,” I said to her before leaving.

Sometimes, being the eldest in the family is not easy. There are many responsibilities that you need to take care of, which can be tiring at times.

I went inside our house after cleaning and they were still eating. I sat down in a chair and got my food.

lAldee, Angel told me that you want to be mayor of Zamboanga City soon,” my mother said.

“Yes, Mama, I want to follow in my father’s footsteps,” I replied.

“Are you sure, Aldee? Being the mayor of Zamboanga City is not easy. You will deal with lots of paperwork, sign documents, and face the crowd,” my father said.

“But if that’s what you want, then I will support you,” Papa added.

“Muchísimas gracias (thank you), Papa,” I said and hugged him.

“Study well, Aldee,” he replied.

I have chosen to pursue a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science in college. This is the best degree program for me because I want to become a lawyer and study in Cebu City.

I decided to keep my decision to study in Cebu City a secret from my parents until after my graduation.

I know that it will be difficult to study in a city where I don’t speak its language, Cebuano. Our mother tongue here in Zamboanga City is Chavacano, a Spanish-based creole. This is why our city is also known as “Asia's Latin City.”

Dinner was over, and it was Angel Grace’s turn to wash the dishes while I prepared my things for school the next day to attend our graduation orientation.

While scrolling through my mother’s phone, I saw some announcements from our school and found out that I was the class valedictorian! I was surprised and delighted.

”Mom, Dad, look!” I exclaimed.

“Wow, Aldee, congratulations! You made it. We’re so proud of you,” my mother said. They were very happy with the news.

The next day, my mother woke me up and reminded me about the orientation.

I went straight to the bathroom while my mother cooked breakfast for me.

After taking a shower, I went to my bedroom to put on my uniform and eat my breakfast.

“Hurry up, Aldee! Your dad is waiting for you in the car!” my mom shouted from downstairs.

I was brushing my teeth at the time and in a hurry as well. I grabbed some of my things and went to the car.

Visayas Art Fair 2023, Bodega Caravan holds a press conference

The Visayas Art Fair (VAF) and Bodega Caravan’s four-day event commenced with a press conference at Horizons Cafe, Oakridge Business Park, on Thursday, November 9.

The Chairwoman of Cebu Design Week (CDW), Maria Luisa Booth, shared the core themes of art, culture, and design.

”In the past five years, we have opened art fairs, celebrating culture, promoting design, as we had trained shows, designed awards, and collaborated with the three segments: art, design, and culture communities of Cebu,” she said.

Booth also shared her team’s vision of renewing their brand through signature events that are soon to be announced on social media and web platforms.

Following Booth’s remarks, Laurie Boquiren, Chairwoman of VAF, announced the event will have 14 exhibitors from the Visayas, 12 from the National Capital Region (NCR), one from Mindanao, and two international participants from Korea.

“From the very first time, the Luzon Art Fair, the Visayas Art Fair, [and] Mindanao Art Fair—all of these three major art events will converge here in Cebu for the Visayas Art Fair,” she said.

Boquiren added that the three major art fairs are recognized by the National Commission for Culture and Arts (NCCA).

Moreover, the VAF is set to feature art installations along with the illumination event of a 25-foot crotched Christmas tree.

The President of CDW, Christina Gaston, explained that the inspiration for Bodega Caravan stems from the nostalgic allure of traditional traveling wood carts.

”From traditional traveling wood carts that would come to the cities from the province to show and sell to us that’s really where we got the name ‘Bodega Caravan,’” Gaston stated.

The last speaker for the conference, Gil Zaire ‘Butch’ Carungay, the Design Director and Cebu UNESCO City of Design Commissioner, Cebu City Tourism Commission, introduced the Blue Mangoes Award (BMA) as a platform to recognize and reward creativity across various disciplines.

”Entries are currently being accepted from designers and creative entrepreneurs not just in Cebu, but also within Region VI, VII, and VIII,” Carungay said.

Furthermore, Kenneth Cobonpue, a multi-awarded Filipino furniture designer and the Curator of Bodega Design Caravan, will be the speaker for VAF.

The VAF and Bodega Caravan will start on November 23 exclusively for VIPs, while the Bodega Caravan’s sales will begin on November 25.

The event will be open to the general public from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. on November 24–26 at Oakridge Business Park.

Josenians showcase talent, creativity in Dance Battle 2023

Josenians enrolled in the Physical Activity Towards Health and Fitness (PATHFit) course performed conceptual dance presentations for the much-anticipated PATHFit Week Dance Battle 2023 at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak Coliseum on Thursday afternoon, November 9.

Nine classes enrolled in PATHFit 3 Menu of Dance took part in the event under the guidance of PATHFit instructors Ms. Shaina Tolentin and Ms. Louanna Castañares.

The students executed different dance styles they mastered throughout the semester, all cladded with thematic costumes, as they jive and bop on this year’s theme, “Dances Through the Decades.”

Meanwhile, the fifth entry from the Monday 9:30–11:30 a.m. class clinched the champion title with their “Fitness Club” concept, aiming to inspire exercise through dance.

One of the dancers and a Bachelor of Science in Accountancy student, Marey Denise Capuno, shared her experience behind their winning production.

“Lingaw nga kapoy...We had fun together as a class,” she said.

She also mentioned that the activity served as a way for students to hone their “creative minds” and “unity” as a class.

“Nagtinabangay mi tanan ug collaborate sa concept. Over the break, we made sacrifices na mo-take og time para sa success and synchronization sa among dance,” she added.

The USJ-R PE Department organized the PATHFit Week Celebration.

New CPAs round up in testimonial dinner

The recent passers in the September-October 2023 Licensure Examination for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos’ (USJ-R) Certified Public Accountants (CPA) Review Center gathered for a testimonial dinner held at the Casino Español de Cebu on Wednesday, November 8.

The evening was filled with engaging activities, including the CPA Bingo, a creative spin on the classic game. Instead of numbers, they had to achieve various tasks all centered and related to their CPA journey.

One of the newly admitted CPAs and Josenian alumna, Maria Stella Cabague, emphasized the benefit of having a good support system throughout her academic journey.

“Very important gyod ang support system para nako. Despite sa kalisod sa program, sa kadaghang struggles nga na-experience namo, it was all bearable because we were all together,” she said.

Cabague also highlighted the value of relaxation amid academic challenges.

“Every year, we always go somewhere, manglaag mi, mag-recharge mi, para the next year, mas stronger nami. Despite sa kalisod, naa gihapon mi’y something to look forward [to],” she added.

Another Josenian CPA, Lemwhel Saldon, expressed that integrity is the ethical value he will continue to cherish as a CPA.

“There are many instances that our integrity will be compromised. Admittedly, daghan kaayo’g factors na ma-compromise atong integrity, may it be [because of] self-interest, maybe because of our boss, or maybe because of those who are ahead of us. I just hope that when the right time comes, we caution ourselves and muster the courage,” he said.

Meanwhile, CPA Review Center Director Kristine June Uy imparted her message to all the new CPAs.

“To the new Certified Public Accountants, as one journey ends, another one begins. May it be filled [with] much happiness, friendships, and success,” she said, welcoming them in the profession.

Prior to the testimonial dinner, a “Tribute to New CPAs” took place at the Center for Performing Arts (CfPA), where the CPA passers were recognized for their achievements.

The oath-taking ceremony for the new CPA passers will be held on December 11 at Cebu Parklane International Hotel.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

#OnTheGo

USJ-R SSC President wins Cebu Fed elections

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Supreme Student Council (USJ-R SSC) 42nd Congress President, Ninolito Enricko Sanchez was elected as the new Cebu City Federation of Tertiary Supreme Student Government and Councils (CCFTSSGC) President during the SSG Summit 2023 at Golden Prince Hotel Cebu City on Sunday afternoon, November 5.

The event brought together council leaders from various educational institutions to address pressing issues concerning Sugbuanon students and plan future initiatives, including blood donation campaigns and HIV awareness in collaboration with the Cebu City Youth Development Commission (CCYDC).

Sanchez, the President-elect of CCFTSSGC, presented his platform for the establishment of a Student’s Rights and Welfare (STRAW) Hotline to address students’ grievances.

He also expressed his commitment to promoting “social inclusion” and creating safe spaces for minority voices.

“Ang students na gipang-deny og enrollment kay taas ilang hair kay dili fit sa standards sa school and katong mga tawong gipang-discriminate. I wanna fight for these people,” he expressed.

The oath-taking of the newly-elected officers of CCFTSSGC will be held at Fuente Park on December 4.

via Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: USJ-R SSC

#OnTheGo

Josenians showcase talent, creativity in Dance Battle 2023

Josenians enrolled in the Physical Activity Towards Health and Fitness (PATHFit) course performed conceptual dance presentations for the much-anticipated PATHFit Week Dance Battle 2023 at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak Coliseum on Thursday afternoon, November 9.

Nine classes enrolled in PATHFit 3 Menu of Dance took part in the event under the guidance of PATHFit instructors Ms. Shaina Tolentin and Ms. Louanna Castañares.

The students executed different dance styles they mastered throughout the semester, all cladded with thematic costumes, as they jive and bop on this year’s theme, “Dances Through the Decades.”

Meanwhile, the fifth entry from the Monday 9:30–11:30 a.m. class clinched the champion title with their “Fitness Club” concept, aiming to inspire exercise through dance.

One of the dancers and a Bachelor of Science in Accountancy student, Marey Denise Capuno, shared her experience behind their winning production.

“Lingaw nga kapoy...We had fun together as a class,” she said.

She also mentioned that the activity served as a way for students to hone their “creative minds” and “unity” as a class.

“Nagtinabangay mi tanan ug collaborate sa concept. Over the break, we made sacrifices na mo-take og time para sa success and synchronization sa among dance,” she added.

The USJ-R PE Department organized the PATHFit Week Celebration.

via Ava Donalie Ferolino | FORWARD Staff Writer

[LITERARY]

From Zamboanga, with Love
by Louella Grace Eroma | Josenian Contributor

“Angel Grace, what do you want to be when you grow up?” I asked my sister while sitting in the chair in our garden.

“I want to be an architect one day, Kuya Aldee, and build a house for our parents,” she replied with a huge smile on her face.

My sister loves to draw buildings and houses, and she loves math too.

“What about you, Kuya Aldee, what is your dream?” she asked me.

“I want to become a lawyer one day and help the people who need legal advice and other legal assistance. And aside from that, I want to be the mayor of Zamboanga City,” I replied, smiling back at her.

“Wow, that‘s great, Kuya. It’s a long way to becoming the mayor of our city, especially since there are a lot of people fighting for that position. I hope and pray to God and Our Lady of the Pillar for you,” she said.

Yes, we are devotees of Our Lady of the Pillar, our patroness here in Zamboanga City.

Our mother called us for dinner and her voice could be heard outside.

“You go ahead, Angel Grace. I need to clean up the mess first,” I said to her before leaving.

Sometimes, being the eldest in the family is not easy. There are many responsibilities that you need to take care of, which can be tiring at times.

I went inside our house after cleaning and they were still eating. I sat down in a chair and got my food.

lAldee, Angel told me that you want to be mayor of Zamboanga City soon,” my mother said.

“Yes, Mama, I want to follow in my father’s footsteps,” I replied.

“Are you sure, Aldee? Being the mayor of Zamboanga City is not easy. You will deal with lots of paperwork, sign documents, and face the crowd,” my father said.

“But if that’s what you want, then I will support you,” Papa added.

“Muchísimas gracias (thank you), Papa,” I said and hugged him.

“Study well, Aldee,” he replied.

I have chosen to pursue a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science in college. This is the best degree program for me because I want to become a lawyer and study in Cebu City.

I decided to keep my decision to study in Cebu City a secret from my parents until after my graduation.

I know that it will be difficult to study in a city where I don’t speak its language, Cebuano. Our mother tongue here in Zamboanga City is Chavacano, a Spanish-based creole. This is why our city is also known as “Asia's Latin City.”

Dinner was over, and it was Angel Grace’s turn to wash the dishes while I prepared my things for school the next day to attend our graduation orientation.

While scrolling through my mother’s phone, I saw some announcements from our school and found out that I was the class valedictorian! I was surprised and delighted.

”Mom, Dad, look!” I exclaimed.

“Wow, Aldee, congratulations! You made it. We’re so proud of you,” my mother said. They were very happy with the news.

The next day, my mother woke me up and reminded me about the orientation.

I went straight to the bathroom while my mother cooked breakfast for me.

After taking a shower, I went to my bedroom to put on my uniform and eat my breakfast.

“Hurry up, Aldee! Your dad is waiting for you in the car!” my mom shouted from downstairs.

I was brushing my teeth at the time and in a hurry as well. I grabbed some of my things and went to the car.

As I made my way to school, I was met with a sea of students, all rushing to get to class. The crowd was so thick that I was nearly late. Luckily, I arrived safely after five minutes.

While walking to my classroom, I almost fell down the stairs.

Fortunately, Jahida, a Tausug girl who has been my confidante and best friend since grade school, saw me.

Jahida asked if I was alright, and I smiled in reply.

“Alhamdulillah, Aldee. I’m glad nothing bad happened to you,” she said.

I continued on my way to class.

Our class adviser was observing us and waiting for our principal.

“Class, please minimize your noise,” our adviser said. But no one was listening to her.

Our class adviser was furious, having repeatedly told us to quiet down.

“Please have discipline. You are now about to enter college life, but your behavior still looks like that of high school students. Please,” she said to us.

Then the principal came to our classroom and said, “What's all the commotion about here?” Everyone was silent.

The graduation orientation has begun, and the speakers are presenting their agenda and the details of our graduation ceremony.

“For the practice, we will start on Monday at one in the afternoon. Everyone must join the graduation practice, otherwise, you cannot attend the graduation ceremony. This is only one round of practice,” the principal said.

“And everyone must attend the baccalaureate mass, too. Attendance will be checked in there, as well as the distribution of the garlands,” she added.

Since we were already informed of what to do, we were dismissed early by the principal.

My mom decided to pick me up at our school since my dad couldn’t due to his heavy workload at the city hall.

We were going to the pueblo (town) to wait for my dad, since his work ends at 5 p.m.

“Mang kunambre io (Mom, I’m hungry),” I said.

“Io tamen kunambre ya noy (I’m hungry too, son),” she replied.

Our stomachs were growling, and we were hungry. So we headed to the mall in search of food, but the restaurants were packed and the prices were high. My mom suggested we go to Paseo del Mar instead.

My dad texted me that he was about to leave his office.

Sender: Dad

Aldee, please tell your mom that I’m almost done with my work here. I’ll go out at 5 p.m. and also please tell your mom that we’ll go to Pasonanca later on. Meet me at the entrance of the city hall. I love you.

Sent to: Aldee

“Mom, Dad texted me and said he’s almost out. We'll meet him at the city hall entrance,” I informed my mother.

“Okay, let him know we're on our way,” she replied.

Sender: Aldee

Dad, I just told Mom about this and she said we'll go there. We're now at Paseo del Mar eating. See you later, Dad.

Sent to: Dad

As I looked around the town, I smiled.

I really love my city, and I'm proud to be a Zamboangueño.

At five o’clock in the afternoon, we met up with my dad.

“Hello, Dad. How’s work?" I asked him.

“Very tiring, Aldee,” he replied.

“How's your orientation? Anyway, congratulations in advance for making it, and for moving on to your next journey.” He said and hugged me.

My dad seemed to be struggling to say something to me.

“What is it, Dad?” I asked.

He couldn't hide it anymore.

“Anak, your mom and I have decided to send you to Cebu City to study. We know it's your dream.”

Wait, what? How did he know? I haven’t even told them about it yet, but I’m very happy. I put a huge smile on my face and jumped with joy.

“Really, Dad? For real?” I still couldn’t believe it was true.

“Yes, anak, it‘s true. You deserve it,” Mom said.

I hugged both of them and thanked them.

“Thank you so much, Mom and Dad. I promise I’ll do my best in Cebu City for college.”

“You’re welcome, our future mayor of Zamboanga City. Do well with your studies,” Dad replied.

I hugged them again with a big smile on my face.

Illustration by Karina Adel Vestil | FORWARD Staff Artist

Then the principal came to our classroom and said, “What's all the commotion about here?” Everyone was silent.

The graduation orientation has begun, and the speakers are presenting their agenda and the details of our graduation ceremony.

“For the practice, we will start on Monday at one in the afternoon. Everyone must join the graduation practice, otherwise, you cannot attend the graduation ceremony. This is only one round of practice,” the principal said.

“And everyone must attend the baccalaureate mass, too. Attendance will be checked in there, as well as the distribution of the garlands,” she added.

Since we were already informed of what to do, we were dismissed early by the principal.

My mom decided to pick me up at our school since my dad couldn’t due to his heavy workload at the city hall.

We were going to the pueblo (town) to wait for my dad, since his work ends at 5 p.m.

“Mang kunambre io (Mom, I’m hungry),” I said.

“Io tamen kunambre ya noy (I’m hungry too, son),” she replied.

Our stomachs were growling, and we were hungry. So we headed to the mall in search of food, but the restaurants were packed and the prices were high. My mom suggested we go to Paseo del Mar instead.

My dad texted me that he was about to leave his office.

Sender: Dad

Aldee, please tell your mom that I’m almost done with my work here. I’ll go out at 5 p.m. and also please tell your mom that we’ll go to Pasonanca later on. Meet me at the entrance of the city hall. I love you.

Sent to: Aldee

“Mom, Dad texted me and said he’s almost out. We'll meet him at the city hall entrance,” I informed my mother.

“Okay, let him know we're on our way,” she replied.

Sender: Aldee

Dad, I just told Mom about this and she said we'll go there. We're now at Paseo del Mar eating. See you later, Dad.

Sent to: Dad

As I looked around the town, I smiled.

I really love my city, and I'm proud to be a Zamboangueño.

At five o’clock in the afternoon, we met up with my dad.

“Hello, Dad. How’s work?" I asked him.

“Very tiring, Aldee,” he replied.

“How's your orientation? Anyway, congratulations in advance for making it, and for moving on to your next journey.” He said and hugged me.

My dad seemed to be struggling to say something to me.

“What is it, Dad?” I asked.

He couldn't hide it anymore.

“Anak, your mom and I have decided to send you to Cebu City to study. We know it's your dream.”

Wait, what? How did he know? I haven’t even told them about it yet, but I’m very happy. I put a huge smile on my face and jumped with joy.

“Really, Dad? For real?” I still couldn’t believe it was true.

“Yes, anak, it‘s true. You deserve it,” Mom said.

I hugged both of them and thanked them.

“Thank you so much, Mom and Dad. I promise I’ll do my best in Cebu City for college.”

“You’re welcome, our future mayor of Zamboanga City. Do well with your studies,” Dad replied.

I hugged them again with a big smile on my face.

Visayas Art Fair 2023, Bodega Caravan holds a press conference

The Visayas Art Fair (VAF) and Bodega Caravan’s four-day event commenced with a press conference at Horizons Cafe, Oakridge Business Park, on Thursday, November 9.

The Chairwoman of Cebu Design Week (CDW), Maria Luisa Booth, shared the core themes of art, culture, and design.

”In the past five years, we have opened art fairs, celebrating culture, promoting design, as we had trained shows, designed awards, and collaborated with the three segments: art, design, and culture communities of Cebu,” she said.

Booth also shared her team’s vision of renewing their brand through signature events that are soon to be announced on social media and web platforms.

Following Booth’s remarks, Laurie Boquiren, Chairwoman of VAF, announced the event will have 14 exhibitors from the Visayas, 12 from the National Capital Region (NCR), one from Mindanao, and two international participants from Korea.

“From the very first time, the Luzon Art Fair, the Visayas Art Fair, [and] Mindanao Art Fair—all of these three major art events will converge here in Cebu for the Visayas Art Fair,” she said.

Boquiren added that the three major art fairs are recognized by the National Commission for Culture and Arts (NCCA).

Moreover, the VAF is set to feature art installations along with the illumination event of a 25-foot crotched Christmas tree.

The President of CDW, Christina Gaston, explained that the inspiration for Bodega Caravan stems from the nostalgic allure of traditional traveling wood carts.

”From traditional traveling wood carts that would come to the cities from the province to show and sell to us that’s really where we got the name ‘Bodega Caravan,’” Gaston stated.

The last speaker for the conference, Gil Zaire ‘Butch’ Carungay, the Design Director and Cebu UNESCO City of Design Commissioner, Cebu City Tourism Commission, introduced the Blue Mangoes Award (BMA) as a platform to recognize and reward creativity across various disciplines.

”Entries are currently being accepted from designers and creative entrepreneurs not just in Cebu, but also within Region VI, VII, and VIII,” Carungay said.

Furthermore, Kenneth Cobonpue, a multi-awarded Filipino furniture designer and the Curator of Bodega Design Caravan, will be the speaker for VAF.

The VAF and Bodega Caravan will start on November 23 exclusively for VIPs, while the Bodega Caravan’s sales will begin on November 25.

The event will be open to the general public from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. on November 24–26 at Oakridge Business Park.

New CPAs round up in testimonial dinner

The recent passers in the September-October 2023 Licensure Examination for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos’ (USJ-R) Certified Public Accountants (CPA) Review Center gathered for a testimonial dinner held at the Casino Español de Cebu on Wednesday, November 8.

The evening was filled with engaging activities, including the CPA Bingo, a creative spin on the classic game. Instead of numbers, they had to achieve various tasks all centered and related to their CPA journey.

One of the newly admitted CPAs and Josenian alumna, Maria Stella Cabague, emphasized the benefit of having a good support system throughout her academic journey.

“Very important gyod ang support system para nako. Despite sa kalisod sa program, sa kadaghang struggles nga na-experience namo, it was all bearable because we were all together,” she said.

Cabague also highlighted the value of relaxation amid academic challenges.

“Every year, we always go somewhere, manglaag mi, mag-recharge mi, para the next year, mas stronger nami. Despite sa kalisod, naa gihapon mi’y something to look forward [to],” she added.

Another Josenian CPA, Lemwhel Saldon, expressed that integrity is the ethical value he will continue to cherish as a CPA.

“There are many instances that our integrity will be compromised. Admittedly, daghan kaayo’g factors na ma-compromise atong integrity, may it be [because of] self-interest, maybe because of our boss, or maybe because of those who are ahead of us. I just hope that when the right time comes, we caution ourselves and muster the courage,” he said.

Meanwhile, CPA Review Center Director Kristine June Uy imparted her message to all the new CPAs.

“To the new Certified Public Accountants, as one journey ends, another one begins. May it be filled [with] much happiness, friendships, and success,” she said, welcoming them in the profession.

Prior to the testimonial dinner, a “Tribute to New CPAs” took place at the Center for Performing Arts (CfPA), where the CPA passers were recognized for their achievements.

The oath-taking ceremony for the new CPA passers will be held on December 11 at Cebu Parklane International Hotel.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

USJ-R SSC President wins Cebu Fed elections

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Supreme Student Council (USJ-R SSC) 42nd Congress President, Ninolito Enricko Sanchez was elected as the new Cebu City Federation of Tertiary Supreme Student Government and Councils (CCFTSSGC) President during the SSG Summit 2023 at Golden Prince Hotel Cebu City on Sunday afternoon, November 5.

The event brought together council leaders from various educational institutions to address pressing issues concerning Sugbuanon students and plan future initiatives, including blood donation campaigns and HIV awareness in collaboration with the Cebu City Youth Development Commission (CCYDC).

Sanchez, the President-elect of CCFTSSGC, presented his platform for the establishment of a Student’s Rights and Welfare (STRAW) Hotline to address students’ grievances.

He also expressed his commitment to promoting “social inclusion” and creating safe spaces for minority voices.

“Ang students na gipang-deny og enrollment kay taas ilang hair kay dili fit sa standards sa school and katong mga tawong gipang-discriminate. I wanna fight for these people,” he expressed.

The oath-taking of the newly-elected officers of CCFTSSGC will be held at Fuente Park on December 4.

Jaguars falter against Webmasters, 59-73

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars fell short against the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters, 59-73, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Basketball game on Tuesday evening, November 7, at the Cebu Coliseum.

The USJ-R Jaguars absorbed their second loss in seven games as they now sit at the third spot this season, behind the defending champions, the University of the Visayas (UV) Green Lancers (6-0), while the Webmasters are still undefeated (8-0).

Anchoring on the offense of their team captain Justine Langres, along with Klein Gordillo, and Elmer Echavez, had an excellent start as they capped off the opening period with a five-point lead (20-15) and stretched it to leave the Webmasters with eight points (34-26) by halftime.

However, the Jaguars turned cold at the start of the second half as some had foul troubles, which made a loophole in the team’s performance.

Their collapsed offense and defense in the third quarter also created a turning point in the match, allowing the Webmasters to eventually reduce the gap.

“Weakness sa team karon [kay] daghan kaayo'g turnovers, 'nya ang pinakadako sad nga problema is wala'y leadership ang point guards instead nga sila ang mag-coach sa sulod [sa court] nya mataranta na. Dako kaayo'g impact ba and at least kana ma-practice na,” Banua said.

The Webmasters took advantage of this dilemma and erased the Jaguars' advantage to one point, 42-41, before completely taking over the third period.

The opposing squad then went on to build a 13-point lead, 57-44, heading into the final period.

Meanwhile, one of the Jaguars' reliable guards, Karl Ventura, suffered an injury when he dislocated his right index finger during the third period as he attempted to poke the ball from the hands of UC's Ricofer Sordilla.

Despite the Jaguars’ effort in the fourth period through Echavez, Langres, and Karl Cabulao, managing to cut the lead at 56-65, the Webmasters quickly responded with an 8-1 run to seal their victory.

Echavez scored a total of 13 points, while Gordillo added 10 in their losing efforts.

Jaguars' Coach Melo Banua also shared that they will still “fight” and “prepare” for the next game and if the team wants to win, they should step up.

“Dili gihapon mi mo-give up, dako gihapon og chance ang team nga makasulod sa top 4. Also, [with] the team chemistry sa point guard and skills sa mga bata, kay daghan [pa] kaayo ta'g malabay na bola,” he said.

The Jaguars will have a chance at redemption as they take on the Benedicto College (BC) Cheetahs on November 12 at the same venue.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Lady Jaguars earn first win in Cesafi 23 Women’s Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Lady Jaguars swept the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats, 3-0, in their first Cesafi 23 Women’s Volleyball match at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Sunday, November 5.

Crossword of Choices: The Growth of an Indomitable Spirit
by Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Time-walking on a seemingly “deja vu” adventure as if he is a game character who respawned in the exact same arena was not an easy adjustment for 24-year-old gamer Tristan Seth Fernandez.

His new encounters inside the campus are a testament now as he embarks on the same journey as it was seven years ago.

From the pursuit of his career in the eSports industry to achieving his dream to become a professor, Tristan’s story is a paragon of resiliency that teaches Josenians how to turn setbacks into opportunities and how to turn those stumbling blocks into stepping stones toward their goals.

The Baffling Dilemma

Reminiscing a certain time frame when he is tested on whether to continue his studies or pursue a career in the eSports industry marked the start of this life-changing dilemma.

At the age of 18, Tristan encountered this formidable challenge that would surely change the course of his destiny, but he tended to surmount it by sacrificing an important part of his life—education over his career.

This decision was heavily influenced by the fact that he’s a late enrollee with an immense school workload to catch up to, even worth mentioning that his chosen program Mass Communication wasn’t aligned with his dream profession to become a professor.

Aside from that, he also shared that his unfortunate financial situation was also the “toughest hindrance” in his school journey.

“Wala ko’y bawn sauna, ambot lang ngano wa ko’y bawn kwarta. Akong klase hantod alas 8 pa sa gabii tas akong money is pang one ride lang sa jeep," he expressed.

Having made a bold decision in the past and considering all influencing factors, Tristan remained committed to hound what he loves doing with no regrets.

Maximizing the Quest for Opportunities

Moving out at such a young age, Tristan somehow found a way to support himself through accepting side jobs.

He made a remarkable name in the eSports industry and accepted notable projects that propelled him to the top.

Tristan worked as a broadcast talent for Mineski and took management roles in companies like RUMBLE ROYALE, AP. Bren, and Cebu’s very own South.gg and even coached Cebuano DOTA teams.

These were the fruits of his labor, an indicator that he was on the right path.

Between 2018 and 2020, he achieved multiple successes, including being the Grand Champion of The Mayor’s Cup 2019, securing the 1st Runner-up position in the Farming Simulator League (FSL) Season 2 qualifiers, and clinching the 2nd Runner-up titles in both the Road to The Nationals Electronic Sports and Gaming Summit (ESGS) and the Acer Predator Cup (APC) 2018.

Tristan viewed this portion of his life as the “sweets of his success.”

Little did they know that there is more to his story than what meets the eye. These attainments were only made possible because of the nights Tristan spent by “sleeping in between jobs.”

Of course, life is not all sweets; it is also about meeting the pressing need to survive a bitter reality. Tristan worked as a barista during the day and a customer representative at night. Life was tough back then for an 18-year-old guy who kept trying to decipher the way out of the labyrinth.

Amidst the pending hardships, he stayed optimistic along the way all in the hope of reaching the finish line. Tristan intensified how much he thrived during those times, yet feeling no amount of exhaustion at all.

“I didn't really feel burnt out or overworked [because] I knew I was working towards something very achievable,” he said.

When one is tested with a tremendous grip of tribulations, their maturity grows, and through these difficulties, they greatly hone their growth as an individual.

Euphoric with achieving more than he expected, he felt that there was still a need for him to go back to his studies.

The Call to U-turn Destination

For anyone who aspires to achieve their aspirations, know that they are valid, even if you encounter setbacks on your path, there’s always a chance to redirect and find purpose moving forward.

Determination is a potent component in this life full of twists and turns, but each challenge that one encounters is an opportunity to learn and grow.

“Whatever I set my mind to, and [if] given a chance to do better this time around, I will,” Fernandez stated.

Being a 24-year-old returnee this academic year brings the “slightest of shame” for him, but this did not deter him from trying again and pursuing his dream of becoming a professor.

“I’m embracing the shamelessness of it. This is me right now. I’m old, and I am getting my life on track,” he added.

In the pursuit of goals, age is never a determining factor.

As long as there is a willingness to strive for better opportunities, growth, and transformation, it remains boundless.

Throughout those experiences, he left a quote that he now instills to motivate him to persevere to finish his education this time.

“On the path towards fulfillment, I am taking the scenic route,” he proudly expressed.

This story is an example that there is no easy way to accomplish goals; there should be obstacles obstructing for us to learn a new lesson, and if ever we make a mistake, at least we come back stronger to break whatever barriers impede us from achieving completion.

“There’s no shame in stepping back; most times it’s how we muster the force to go forward,” Fernandez encouraged.

For anyone who has an ambition and it’s so far away and high up, it’s normal to be tired.

One day you’re gonna look from your feet and you’ll be at your destination.

Tristan Seth Fernandez may be a gamer, but he's now a character in a game of reality, maneuvering the course of his own life.

Jaguars outplay Fighting Maroons in Cesafi Men's Volleyball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars claimed victory against the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Fighting Maroons, 3-0, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Volleyball tournament at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Saturday, November 4.

The USJ-R Jaguars withstood the persistent rally of the UPC Fighting Maroons with a series of dynamic hits, securing a 25-18 triumph in the first set.

Jaguars' Ehdrienne Suarez and Ed Vincent Flores delivered strong service aces and powerful attacks for the team, including swift dumps.

Despite a few service errors, the Jaguars increased their offensive campaign in the second set and left their opponent with a 12-point lead, 25-13.

The Jaguars also cemented their win over the Fighting Maroons with defensive blocks, finishing a 25-15 in the final set.

Before the match, Jaguars' Coach Roland Potot made the decision to bench the starting six and instead fielded the second team throughout the game, as some of the starting players failed to meet the pre-match training requirements.

“Akong gitan-aw sa ani nga team is to give them a chance as we need the right attitude sa game and practices. Dili lang skill ang atong gitrabaho as a team, also on their character as well,” Potot said.

Meanwhile, Suarez, an open spiker for the Jaguars, shared the team's commitment in their upcoming games.

“In this season, our goal is to keep it low-key this time kay mag-work hard sa mi sa mga lacking sa among team and make more progress pa jud,” he said.

The Jaguars will next face the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on November 18 at the same venue.
